    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-06-05T17:13:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-06-05T17:13:00-05:00" n="505"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d505">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.61/6–552: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 505<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Soviet Union</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d505fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BW1"
                            >Barbour</persName> and <persName>Henry</persName> (<gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_EE1">EE</gloss>) and
                        cleared by <persName corresp="#p_BCE1">Bohlen</persName> (<gloss
                            target="#t_C1">C</gloss>), <persName corresp="#p_MHT1"
                            >Matthews</persName> (<gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>), <persName
                            corresp="#p_NPH1">Nitze</persName> (<gloss target="#t_SP1">S/P</gloss>),
                        Hickerson (<gloss target="#t_UNA1">UNA</gloss>), <persName corresp="#p_JPC1"
                            >Jessup</persName> (<gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>/<gloss
                            target="#t_A1">A</gloss>), and <persName corresp="#p_PJB1"
                            >Phillips</persName> (<gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss>). Secretary
                            <persName corresp="#p_AD1">Acheson</persName> signed the
                        telegram.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-06-05T18:13:00-04:00"
                            >June 5, 1952—6:13 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>846. Re Embtel 1906.<note n="2" xml:id="d505fn2">
                        <ref target="#d504">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> We have been deeply impressed by <gloss target="#t_ur1"
                        >ur</gloss> series tels re present intensity Sov propaganda attacks on US.
                        <gloss target="#t_ur1">Ur</gloss> suggestion of Presidential statement on
                    subj has been given careful consideration with full realization weight <gloss
                        target="#t_ur1">ur</gloss> opinion in matter.</p>
                <p>However, as we see it, Sov campaign among other things designed (1) by maximum
                    provocativeness to intimidate Free World opinion through general increase in
                    tensions and war of nerves at this particular time, and (2) by singling out US
                    as target to separate US from its Free World Allies and polarize issues toward
                    bilateral US–USSR conflict. If such is case, special statement at Presidential
                    level might play into Sov hands by (1) increasing apprehensions in certain
                    quarters of opinion where fear already exists of excessive US combativeness and
                    (2) tending to accept and accentuate, by its unilateral nature, Sov contention
                    that lines are drawn directly between Moscow and Wash.</p>
                <p>In circumstances, on balance, we are inclined to prefer action in <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> along line <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 829<note n="3" xml:id="d505fn3">
                        <ref target="#d503">Document 503</ref>.</note> on which now awaiting
                    reaction UK before exploring with other friendly <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                        >SC</gloss> members. As you indicate final para <gloss target="#t_ur1"
                        >ur</gloss> 1909<note n="4" xml:id="d505fn4">See <ref target="#d504fn2"
                            >footnote 2, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</ref>
                    </note> this wld not be incompatible <gloss target="#t_ur1">ur</gloss>
                    suggestion and wld not preclude later Presidential statement if that course shld
                    subsequently appear desirable.<note n="5" xml:id="d505fn5">In telegram 1971,
                        June 9, Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_KGF1">Kennan</persName> observed:
                        “Fully appreciate force of considerations invoked in Dept’s 846 re possible
                        US statement about Sov propaganda campaign and gladly concede best course
                        may be to remain silent.” (611.61/6–952)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
